<chapter id="vlc"><title id="tvlc">The VideoLAN Client</title>

<sect1><title>Installing the VideoLAN Client</title>

  &install-vlc;

</sect1>

<sect1>
 <title>Running the VideoLAN Client</title>
 <sect2><title></title>
  <para>
If you are under Windows, a vlc icon has been created in the start menu. To start the VLC, simply double-click on it.
  </para>
  <para>If you use Debian GNU/Linux and you have used the deb or the RPM package, a shortcut has also been created
  </para>
  <para>You will also find an icon under Mac OS X</para>
  <para>
The Graphical Interface of the VideoLAN Client is simple to use.</para>
 </sect2>
 <sect2><title>Read a File</title>

  <para>To read a MPEG stream stored on a file, click on the "File" Button, and select the location of your stream. You can download a sample stream at the address: <ulink url=" ftp://ftp.videolan.org/pub/videolan/streams/presentation/presentation_short.vob" > ftp://ftp.videolan.org/pub/videolan/streams/presentation/presentation_short.vob </ulink></para>
</sect2>
<sect2><title>Read a DVD</title>

<para>To read a  DVD or a VCD,  click on the "Disc" Icon.  Choose VCD or
DVD and provide the path to your drive. Under Windows, it will look like
D:\ whereas  under Linux,  it could  be /dev/dvd.</para>

<para>Please note,  that if
you  are  running Linux,  you  must  have  write  access to  the  device
corresponding to your DVD drive. For that,  you should be in the disk or
cdrom group (look at the permissions in /dev). As root, do :</para>

<screen>
<prompt>#</prompt><userinput> adduser my_login disk_or_cdrom</userinput>
</screen>

<para>Don't forget to restart your session then</para>

<para>If  you  are  running  Windows  NT/2000 or  XP,  you  must  have
administrator rights (i.e. log in as administrator or as a user with
administrator rights).</para>


</sect2>

 <sect2><title>Use the command-line</title>
  <para>
If you don't use the graphical interface, you can use the command-line to read streams with the VideoLAN Client
  </para>

  <para>Type this at the prompt</para>
  <screen><prompt>%</prompt><userinput> vlc name_of_your_file</userinput></screen>

  <para>or, for a DVD:</para>
  <screen> <prompt>%</prompt><userinput> vlc dvd:path_to_dvd</userinput></screen>
  <para>with path_to_dvd like D:\ for Windows, or /dev/dvd for Linux</para>
  <para>To get a list of the availables options, you can use</para>
  <screen> <prompt>%</prompt><userinput> vlc --help</userinput></screen>
  <para>You can also use the command-line to start the graphical interface, by simply typing:</para>
  <screen><prompt>%</prompt><userinput> vlc</userinput></screen>
 </sect2>
 <sect2><title>Troubleshooting</title>

<para>If VLC doesn't work for you:</para>
<itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>First, try to launch it in verbose mode</para>

<screen>
<prompt>%</prompt><userinput> vlc -vvv</userinput></screen>

<para>and try to understand the error message</para>
</listitem>

<listitem><para>Then, read the <ulink url="http://www.videolan.org/doc/vlc-howto/">VideoLAN Client HOWTO</ulink> and vlc FAQ (also available in the sources, file "FAQ")
</para>

</listitem>

<listitem><para>If you can't find out the problem, explain your problem in English in the mailing-list vlc@videolan.org with the output of vlc -vvv.</para>
</listitem>


  </itemizedlist>
 </sect2>
</sect1>
